{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5103","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:23 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:23 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">The secondary verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་</span> “to stay” has an aspectual sense. The main verb, which is followed by <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་</span>, must take the past tense. The connective <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནས་</span> may optionally be placed between the main verb and the secondary verb: Verb + (<span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནས་</span>) <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་</span> + Auxiliary.</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The secondary verb <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་</span> indicates that an action that was begun in the past <em>is in the process of happening</em> either in the present or from a past point of reference, or that the state of affairs resulting from this action is still present. The secondary verb may be followed by:</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">(a) perfective auxiliaries: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་པ་ཡིན་</span> (egophoric), <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་པ་རེད་</span> (assertive), <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་སོང་</span> (testimonial)</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">(b) perfect auxiliaries: <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་ཡོད་</span> (egophoric), <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་ཡོད་རེད་</span> (assertive), <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བསྡད་བཞག་</span> (inferential)</p> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The former constructions (a) may be translated by the perfective, and the latter (b) by the imperfective or the present perfect continuous according to the context. The use of adverbs such as “still” may help to convey the meaning of these constructions.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">རྡོ་རྗེ་ནང་ལ་ལོག་ཡོང་དུས་ཉི་མས་དེབ་བལྟས་(ནས་)བསྡད་བཞག</span> “When Dorjé got back home, Nyima was still reading a book.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁ་ས་ཁྲོམ་ལ་ཐུག་དུས་མོ་རང་གིས་མར་ཉོས་(ནས་)བསྡད་བཞག</span> “Yesterday, when I met her in the market, she was buying butter.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མོ་རང་ངུས་ནས་བསྡད་པ་རེད།</span> “She’s been crying constantly.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">འཛིན་གྲྭའི་ནང་ལ་སྐད་ཆ་བཤད་ནས་བསྡད་པ་རེད།</span> “He’s been talking all the time in class.” </li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">The construction may also indicate a resulting state.</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁོ་རང་ན་བསྡད་བཞག</span> “He’s still unwell.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མོ་རང་ལང་བསྡད་བཞག</span> “She’s up.” (Literally: “She got up and she’s stayed up.” Compare this with the sentence <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མོ་རང་ཡར་ལངས་སོང་།</span> “She got up.”)</li> </ul>","title":""}]}
